<DOC><DOCNO> AP891011-0292 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-89 2245EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Zenith-Computers     10-11 0213</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Zenith-Computers,0222</SECOND><HEAD>Zenith Introduces More Powerful Laptop Computer</HEAD><DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Zenith Data Systems, the soon-to-be-soldcomputer division of Zenith Electronics Corp., unveiled four newpersonal computers Wednesday, including the industry's firstbattery-powered laptop model based on the powerful Intel 80386SXmicroprocessor.   Zenith, the world's largest seller of battery-powered laptopcomputers, said the new 12.1-pound SupersPort SX laptop _ whichweighs 16.8 pounds with its battery _ could operate for more thanthree hours on the battery before it needs recharging.   The model will be available with a 3.5-inch floppy disc driveand either a 40 megabyte or 100 megabyte hard-disc drive at asuggested retail price of about $6,800 and $7,400, respectively.   Spokesman Matt Mirapaul said Japan's Toshiba and NEC also makelaptop-size computers based on the 386SX microprocessor but neitherruns on a battery.   Glenview-based Zenith also introduced a desktop workstationbased on the 386SX microprocesser, a faster version of itsTurbosPort 386 laptop with an improved display and a faster versionof its SupersPort 286 laptop with improved display.   Zenith announced Oct. 2 it had agreed to sell its computeroperations to France's Groupe Bull for up to $635 million.   The sale will leave Zenith with its consumer electronicsbusiness. Zenith is the last major U.S.-based televisionmanufacturer.</TEXT></DOC>